{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17527619","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17527619"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:31:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:31:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14208"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14208","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14208"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.01,0.01,0.13,0.55]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6894"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104067"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6894","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6894"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14208"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86386"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"928"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4989"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"5351"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"11260"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12918"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15750"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36108"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36109"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104067","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104067"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman is preparing to give a presentation at a medical conference in Brisbane, Queensland. She is not Indigenous but wants to show respect for the Traditional Owners of the land. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate Acknowledgement of Country for her to use at the beginning of her presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["A general acknowledgement of all Indigenous peoples across Australia","An acknowledgement specific to the Indigenous peoples of another major Australian city","An acknowledgement of Indigenous peoples from a different state","A brief statement recognising Indigenous peoples as the first inhabitants","An acknowledgement specific to the local Indigenous peoples of Brisbane"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAn Acknowledgement of Country is an important cultural protocol that shows respect for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples as the Traditional Owners and Custodians of the land. It is appropriate for both Indigenous and non-Indigenous people to give an Acknowledgement of Country.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecorrect option\u003C/strong\u003E acknowledges the specific Traditional Owner groups of the Brisbane area. This acknowledgement is specific to the location of the conference and demonstrates respect and recognition for the local Indigenous groups.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe option for \u003Cstrong\u003Ea general acknowledgement of all Indigenous peoples across Australia\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as it lacks specificity to the local area where the conference is taking place.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESimilarly, \u003Cstrong\u003Ean acknowledgement specific to the Indigenous peoples of another major Australian city\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as it does not recognise the Traditional Owners of the land where the conference is being held.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAn acknowledgement of Indigenous peoples from a different state\u003C/strong\u003E is also incorrect as it does not relate to the specific location of the event.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Ea brief statement recognising Indigenous peoples as the first inhabitants\u003C/strong\u003E is true, it is not specific to the local area and does not constitute a proper Acknowledgement of Country.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen giving an Acknowledgement of Country, it\u0027s important to be specific about the local Indigenous groups of the area where the event is taking place. If unsure about the specific groups, it\u0027s acceptable to use a more general acknowledgement, but when the information is available, it\u0027s best to name the Traditional Owner groups explicitly.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acknowledgement of Country is an important cultural protocol that shows respect for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples as the Traditional Owners and Custodians of the land.","The specific wording of an Acknowledgement of Country should reflect the local Indigenous groups of the area.","Acknowledgement of Country can be given by both Indigenous and non-Indigenous people."],"references":["New South Wales Ministry of Health. (2019, July 1). Communicating positively: A guide to appropriate Aboriginal terminology (GL2019_008). Centre for Aboriginal Health. https://www.health.nsw.gov.au/policies/gl/2019/pdf/GL2019_008.pdf","Acknowledgement of Country and Welcome to Country. Reconciliation Australia. [webpage]. 2025. \u003Chttps://www.reconciliation.org.au/reconciliation/acknowledgement-of-country-and-welcome-to-country/\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86386"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14208"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86386","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86386"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-29T11:01:02+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-29T11:01:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6894"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionR